\begin_layout Subsection
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key work in this area comes from Ireland 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

and Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankModel"

\end_inset

.
 Ireland consider an exogenous signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 - which is the signaling factor that causes a consumer to deviate from
 the optimal choice he would have made in absence of signaling.
 This is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

private
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 utility function.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v,w)$
\end_inset

 denotes utility function in a two-commodity world comprising of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (visible) and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 (invisible), whose quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 are consumed respectively, then the utility function in presence of signal
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 can be denoted as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U & =F(f(v,w),s)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This utility function is assumed to hold for all individuals and reflects
 all demand characteristics as well as spectators’ inference about status.
 The signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 itself is represented in terms of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spectator inference function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 -
\begin_inset Formula $g(v)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
s & =f(v,g(v))
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the convexity assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(1-a)\cdot f(v,w)+a\cdot f(v,g(v))$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $0<a<1$
\end_inset

), a budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $w+pv=y$
\end_inset

 and an inference function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v)=g(v)+pv$
\end_inset

 conditions for a signaling equilibrium can be derived.
 The solution (and the calibration which we seek) largely depends on the
 choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot,\cdot)$
\end_inset

.
 For both quasi-linear, homothetic choices, it follows that the equilibrium
 conditions result in significant deviation from private utility maximization
 in the low-income group
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

