\begin_layout Standard
The key task has been that of standardizing consumption and income data.
 While income and consumption data are available per week for UK, the data
 for Tanzania is relatively sparse.
 Only 14% of the total surveyed respondents in Tanzania, for example, is
 on a kind of wage.
 The younger profile of the country has partly accounts for the sparsity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dependence on agrarian income is also evident from a preliminary analysis
 of the panel data.
 A permanent income perspective is to be explored in order to explain the
 consumption patterns.
 The LSMS national panel survey for Tanzania does measure the expected income
 to be used towards this analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key learning from literature survey so far has been the difference in
 perspectives towards between consumption and purchases.
 For the purpose of conspicuous consumption, one may rely on purchases rather
 than consumption - but since permanent income effects can have an influence
 on purchases, a study of purchases without consumption is ruled out.
\end_layout

